Featured resources

Practical information for immediately after a loss

The immediate aftermath of a loved one’s suicide is a challenging, confusing, and painful time. The information below will help get you through the first few days with a better understanding of the things you’re likely to face.

Each year, we honor individuals and organizations that have made a substantial contribution to suicide prevention at our annual Lifesavers Gala. Traditionally, the event is held live in New York City and available to a limited group of attendees. But this year’s Lifesavers Gala is unlike any other – a virtual extravaganza that you can be a part of no matter where you are, with tickets starting at $50. We hope you’ll join us, and be a part of our yearly effort to raise money to continue our important research, advocacy, and education and support programs. Link in bio to get your ticket!

"Before finding Be The Voice, I thought mental illness was something you just kept locked in a vault, and suicidal ideation was taboo. However, hearing someone talk about something so open that affected me, not only drove me to get involved with Be The Voice my freshman year of college, but also made me seek help with the help of some of my friends." -Holly, Butler University Out of the Darkness Campus Walk Chair Help prevent suicide on your campus and find a Campus Walk near you! Link in bio ❤

Today is #TransDayofVisibility. Here at AFSP, we know research shows that anti-transgender discrimination contributes to mental health concerns and suicide risk. Today, we celebrate and lift up our transgender colleagues, family, friends, and neighbors, and let them know their lives matter. Swipe for resources that will not only help you survive, but thrive. 🏳️‍🌈 🏳️‍⚧️
